Chrome Extension Guide: Task Manager
====================================

In this guide, we will build a Chrome extension called "Task Manager" that allows users to view and manage their open tabs and windows in a more efficient way. The extension will show the title, URL, and loading status of each tab, and allow users to close or reload tabs directly from the Task Manager interface.

Getting Started
---------------

To get started, create a new directory on your computer for the Task Manager extension. Inside this directory, create the following subdirectories:
```perl
icons/
options/
popup/
```
We will add the necessary files to each of these directories throughout the guide.

Manifest File
-------------

The first file we need to create is the `manifest.json` file, which will contain metadata about our extension, such as its name, version, and permissions. Create a new file called `manifest.json` in the root directory of your Task Manager extension and add the following code:

```json
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "Task Manager",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "View and manage open tabs and windows in a more efficient way.",
  "icons": {
    "16": "icons/icon16.png",
    "32": "icons/icon32.png",
    "48": "icons/icon48.png",
    "128": "icons/icon128.png"
  },
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"],
    "persistent": false
  },
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["<all_urls>"],
      "js": ["content.js"]
    }
  ],
  "browser_action": {
    "default_icon": "icons/icon48.png",
    "default_popup": "popup/popup.html"
  },
  "permissions": [
    "tabs",
    "storage"
  ]
}
```
This `manifest.json` file defines the following properties:

* `manifest_version`: The version of the manifest file format.
* `name`: The name of the extension.
* `version`: The version of the extension.
* `description`: A short description of the extension.
* `icons`: An object that contains the different icons for the extension.
* `background`: An object that defines the background script for the extension.
* `content_scripts`: An array of objects that define the content scripts for the extension.
* `browser_action`: An object that defines the browser action for the extension, including the icon and popup.
* `permissions`: An array of permissions that the extension requires.

Service Workers
---------------

Service workers are responsible for handling background tasks in a Chrome extension. For our Task Manager extension, we will use a service worker to listen for events and update the UI accordingly. Create a new file called `background.js` in the root directory of your extension and add the following code:

```javascript
// A function to update the Task Manager UI when a tab is updated.
function updateUI(tab) {
  // Get the task with the same tabId as the updated tab.
  const task = tasks.find(t => t.tabId === tab.id);

  // If the task exists, update its properties.
  if (task) {
    task.title = tab.title;
    task.url = tab.url;
    task.loading = tab.status === "loading";

    // Save the updated task to local storage.
    saveTasks();
  }
}

// A function to listen for updated tabs and update the UI.
function listenForTabUpdates() {
  // Listen for the tab updated event.
  chrome.tabs.onUpdated.addListener((tabId, changeInfo, tab) => {
    // Update the UI for the tab if it has a title and is not in the process of loading.
    if (tab.title && !tab.status) {
      updateUI(tab);
    }
  });
}

// A function to listen for new tabs and add them to the Task Manager UI.
function listenForNewTabs() {
  // Listen for the tab created event.
  chrome.tabs.onCreated.addListener((tab) => {
    // Add the tab to the Task Manager UI.
    tasks.push({
      tabId: tab.id,
      title: tab.title,
      url: tab.url,
      loading: tab.status === "loading",
      pinned: tab.pinned,
      active: tab.active
    });

    // Save the updated tasks to local storage.
    saveTasks();
  });
}

// A function to listen for closed tabs and remove them from the Task Manager UI.
function listenForClosedTabs() {
  // Listen for the tab removed event.
  chrome.tabs.onRemoved.addListener((tabId) => {
    // Remove the tab from the Task Manager UI.
    tasks = tasks.filter(t => t.tabId !== tabId);

    // Save the updated tasks to local storage.
    saveTasks();
  });
}

// A function to save the tasks to local storage.
function saveTasks() {
  chrome.storage.local.set({ tasks });
}

// An array to store the tasks.
let tasks = [];

// Load the tasks from local storage.
chrome.storage.local.get("tasks", ({ tasks: storedTasks }) => {
  // If tasks exist in local storage, use them.
  if (storedTasks) {
    tasks = storedTasks;
  }

  // Listen for updated tabs.
  listenForTabUpdates();

  // Listen for new tabs.
  listenForNewTabs();

  // Listen for closed tabs.
  listenForClosedTabs();
});
```
This `background.js` file defines the following functions:

* `updateUI`: A function to update the Task Manager UI when a tab is updated.
* `listenForTabUpdates`: A function to listen for updated tabs and update the UI.
* `listenForNewTabs`: A function to listen for new tabs and add them to the Task Manager UI.
* `listenForClosedTabs`: A function to listen for closed tabs and remove them from the Task Manager UI.
* `saveTasks`: A function to save the tasks to local storage.

Content Script
--------------

Content scripts are responsible for interacting with web pages that the user has open in their browser. For our Task Manager extension, we will use a content script to get the title and URL of the current tab. Create a new file called `content.js` in the root directory of your extension and add the following code:

```javascript
