To access WebSocket topics in your Android app using STOMP and SockJS, you can use a library called "Stomp over WebSocket for Android" which provides support for STOMP protocol over WebSocket. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to use this library:

1. Add the library to your Android project by adding the following dependency in your `build.gradle` file:
```python
implementation 'com.github.NaikSoftware:StompProtocolAndroid:1.6.4'
```
2. Create a Stomp client in your app. Here's an example:
```java
import org.java_websocket.client.WebSocketClient;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshakeHandler;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshake;
import org.java_websocket.exceptions.WebsocketNotConnectedException;

public class MyStompClient extends Stomp {

    private OnMessageListener onMessageListener;

    public MyStompClient(WebSocketClient webSocketClient, ServerHandshakeHandler handshakeHandler) {
        super(webSocketClient, handshakeHandler);
    }

    public void setOnMessageListener(OnMessageListener onMessageListener) {
        this.onMessageListener = onMessageListener;
    }

    @Override
    public void onMessage(String payload) {
        if (onMessageListener != null) {
            onMessageListener.onMessage(payload);
        }
    }

    public void send(String destination, String message) throws WebsocketNotConnectedException {
        super.send(destination, message);
    }

    public interface OnMessageListener {
        void onMessage(String payload);
    }
}
```
3. Create a WebSocket client that connects to your Spring Boot backend. Here's an example:
```java
import org.java_websocket.client.WebSocketClient;
import org.java_websocket.drafts.Draft_17;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshakeHandler;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshake;

public class MyWebSocketClient extends WebSocketClient {

    public MyWebSocketClient(String url) {
        super(url, new Draft_17());
    }

    @Override
    public void onOpen(ServerHandshake handshakedata) {
        // Connection is established. Send STOMP connect message.
        send("CONNECT\n" +
                "accept-version:1.2\n" +
                "heart-beat:10000,10000\n" +
                "\n" +
                "\u0000");
    }

    @Override
    public void onMessage(String message) {
        // Handle incoming STOMP message.
        System.out.println(message);
    }

    @Override
    public void onClose(int code, String reason, boolean remote) {
        // Connection is closed.
        System.out.println("Connection closed: " + reason);
    }

    @Override
    public void onError(Exception ex) {
        // Handle error.
        System.out.println("Error: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
}
```
4. Combine the Stomp client and WebSocket client to create a connection to your Spring Boot backend. Here's an example:
```java
MyWebSocketClient webSocketClient = new MyWebSocketClient("ws://your-spring-boot-backend-url");

ServerHandshakeHandler handshakeHandler = new ServerHandshakeHandler() {
    @Override
    public void onHandshakeRequest(WebSocket webSocket, ServerHandshake handshakedata) {
        // Implement handshake logic.
    }

    @Override
    public void onHandshakeReceived(WebSocket webSocket, ServerHandshake handshakedata) {
        // Handle successful handshake.
    }
};

MyStompClient stompClient = new MyStompClient(webSocketClient, handshakeHandler);
stompClient.setOnMessageListener(new MyStompClient.OnMessageListener() {
    @Override
    public void onMessage(String payload) {
        // Handle incoming message.
        System.out.println(payload);
    }
});

webSocketClient.connect();

// Send STOMP message to subscribe to a topic.
stompClient.send("/topic/your-topic", "{\"subscription\": \"your-subscription\"}");

// Send STOMP message to publish a message.
stompClient.send("/app/your-endpoint", "{\"message\": \"your-message\"}");
```

Note: Make sure to replace `YourWebSocketClient` and `YourStompClient` with your own class names, and replace `ws://your-spring-boot-backend-url` with the URL of your Spring Boot backend. Also, make sure to configure your Spring Boot backend to use the same STOMP version and heart-beat settings as your Android app.

