HTML:
```
<iframe id="myIframe" src="https://www.example.com"></iframe>
```
CSS:
```
#myIframe {
  width: 100%; /* Default width */
  height: 500px;
}
```
JavaScript:
```
// Run this code on load
window.onload = function() {
  var iframe = document.getElementById("myIframe");
  var width = window.innerWidth; // Get the current viewport width

  if (width <= 360) {
    iframe.style.width = "360px";
  } else if (width <= 720) {
    iframe.style.width = "720px";
  } else if (width <= 1400) {
    iframe.style.width = "100%"; // Up to 1400px, use the default 100% width
  } else {
    iframe.style.width = "1400px";
  }
}

// Run this code on resize
window.onresize = function() {
  var iframe = document.getElementById("myIframe");
  var width = window.innerWidth; // Get the current viewport width

  if (width <= 360) {
    iframe.style.width = "360px";
  } else if (width <= 720) {
    iframe.style.width = "720px";
  } else if (width <= 1400) {
    iframe.style.width = "100%"; // Up to 1400px, use the default 100% width
  } else {
    iframe.style.width = "1400px";
  }
}
```
This code will set the width of the iframe to 360px if the viewport is 360px or less, 720px if the viewport is between 361px and 720px, and 100% (up to a maximum of 1400px) if the viewport is between 721px and 1400px. If the viewport is larger than 1400px, the iframe will be set to 1400px.

Note that this code uses the `window.onload` and `window.onresize` events to check the viewport width on load and on resize, respectively. This ensures that the iframe width is updated whenever the viewport is resized.

You may want to adjust the conditions and width values in the code to fit your specific use case.

