To achieve the desired behavior where the navigation bar hides on scroll down and shows on scroll up with a sliding animation, and to disable the animation for pages that don't scroll, you can use JavaScript along with CSS transitions. Here's an example:

First, add the following CSS to your stylesheet:

```css
nav {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  transition: transform 0.3s ease; /* adjust the duration and timing function as desired */
}

nav.hide {
  transform: translateY(-100%);
}
```

Next, add the following JavaScript code to your page:

```javascript
const nav = document.querySelector('nav');
let prevScrollPos = window.pageYOffset;

const hideNav = () => {
  if (window.pageYOffset > prevScrollPos) {
    nav.classList.add('hide');
  } else {
    nav.classList.remove('hide');
  }
  prevScrollPos = window.pageYOffset;
};

const handleScroll = () => {
  if (document.body.scrollHeight > window.innerHeight) {
    hideNav();
  }
};

window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
```

This JavaScript code checks if the page has a scrollbar (`document.body.scrollHeight > window.innerHeight`) before deciding whether to hide the navigation bar on scroll down. This prevents the animation from being applied on short pages that don't scroll.

Additionally, the code only hides the navigation bar if the current scroll position is greater than the previous scroll position. This ensures that the navigation bar only hides when scrolling down and shows when scrolling up.

You can adjust the duration and timing function of the `transform` transition in the CSS to customize the sliding animation.

